    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3049730541" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3049730541" />
    <a title="Asher" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/84179594-asher"><img alt="Asher" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1531586040p2/84179594.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3049730541?book_show_action=true">Nov 15, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Asher" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Asher" href="/user/show/84179594-asher">Asher</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/26894560-the-sorrow-s-garden">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3049730541" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8823236924245350238">The Sorrow&apos;s Garden: A Novel by Anthony Carinhas is a historical suspense and literary fiction book that is set in Germany and New York in the mid 1920&apos;s to late 1930&apos;s, as the Gestapo raid and arrest the family of even the most famous and a twistedly brilliant man named Radulf becomes consumed by a woman named Klara. Narrated in the first person, Radulf Berliner, a serial killer who has rapid cycling through night and day terrors, sexual aggression, and moments of eerily profound clarity, the b</span>
  <span id="freeText8823236924245350238" style="display:none">The Sorrow's Garden: A Novel by Anthony Carinhas is a historical suspense and literary fiction book that is set in Germany and New York in the mid 1920's to late 1930's, as the Gestapo raid and arrest the family of even the most famous and a twistedly brilliant man named Radulf becomes consumed by a woman named Klara. Narrated in the first person, Radulf Berliner, a serial killer who has rapid cycling through night and day terrors, sexual aggression, and moments of eerily profound clarity, the book allows Radulf to divulge the whole of his story in succinct and straightforward exposition. <br /><br /><i>“It was the first time I killed someone, and I didn’t feel remorse for the incident. I had no control over the fact that she couldn’t swim...”</i><br /><br />With his novel The Sorrow's Garden, Anthony Carinhas has written a book that is what I would expect the love child between Bret Easton Ellis' American Psycho and Patricia Highsmith's The Talented Mr Ripley to read like. Cynical and completely deadpan in his delivery, Radulf migrates through his life entirely bankrupt of principle while asserting the use of a higher road among others. For all the ferociousness of his sexuality, he describes the encounters with all the panache of a tepid glass of milk—and it totally works. It thrives. It keeps a reader plowing through the pages. This isn't going to be the book for everyone, but I'm grateful to have picked it up and discovered a new author to fanboy over. Exceptional.<br /><br />Review written for Readers' Favorite.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8823236924245350238" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

